2. High-Level Architecture

Frontend

Web client, desktop client, and mobile apps

Backend (API Layer)
RESTful or gRPC APIs for all client interactions

Core Services
User Service: Handles user data, authentication, permissions
File Service: Handles file metadata, versioning, and operations
Storage Service: Handles actual file storage and retrieval
Sync Service: Handles device synchronization and conflict resolution
Sharing Service: Manages file/folder sharing and permissions
Notification Service: Push/email notifications for sharing, changes
Search Service: Indexes files and metadata for fast search

Data Storage
Metadata: Relational DB (e.g., PostgreSQL, MySQL) for user info, file metadata, permissions, version history
File Storage: Distributed object storage (e.g., AWS S3, HDFS, custom blob store)
Cache: Redis/Memcached for hot metadata and session data
Search Index: Elasticsearch or Solr for fast file search

Other Components
CDN: For fast file delivery and download
Encryption Service: Encrypt files at rest and in transit
Audit/Logging: Track file access, changes, and sharing events


3. Key Design Considerations
============================

Scalability

Use microservices for independent scaling of file, user, and sync services
Use distributed storage for large files and high throughput

Consistency & Reliability

Use strong consistency for file metadata and permissions
Eventual consistency for file sync across devices
File versioning to handle conflicts and rollbacks

Security & Privacy

Encrypt files at rest and in transit

Fine-grained access control and sharing permissions
Audit logs for compliance

Performance

Use CDN for file delivery
Use caching for metadata and frequently accessed files
Asynchronous processing for large file uploads/downloads


4. Example Data Flow: File Upload
=================================
User uploads a file via client.
API authenticates user and checks permissions.
File is split into chunks (for large files).
Chunks are uploaded to distributed storage (e.g., S3).
Metadata (file name, size, owner, version, location) is stored in the metadata DB.
File version/history is updated.
User receives confirmation and file is available for sync/download.


